===Noun===

# A [[rod]] bent into a [[curve]]d shape, typically with one end free and the other end secured to a rope or other attachment.
# A [[loop]] shaped like a hook (1) under certain written [[letter]]s, e.g. ''g'' and ''j''.

====Translations====

*[[German]]: [[Haken]] ''m'' (1)
*[[Interlingua]]: [[croc]] (1); [[uncino]] (1) (as in "wall hook", "hook and eye" etc.); [[hamo]] (1) (for fishing)
*[[Portuguese]]: [[gancho]] ''m'' (1); [[anzol]] ''m'' (1) (for fishing)
*[[Spanish]]: [[gancho]] ''m'' (1)
*[[Tok Pisin]]: [[huk]]

===Transitive verb===

# To [[attach]] a hook to
# To [[catch]] with a hook (''hook a fish'')
# To [[connect]] (''hook into'', ''hook together'')
# To [[meet]] (''hook up'')
# (Usually in passive) To make [[addicted]] (''I'm hooked'').

